{"parse":{"title":"Art in the Streets","pageid":42538952,"revid":838740792,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p><i><b>Art in the Streets</b></i> was an exhibition held at the <a href=\"/wiki/Museum_of_Contemporary_Art_Los_Angeles\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Museum of Contemporary Art Los Angeles\">Museum of Contemporary Art Los Angeles</a> from April 17 to August 8, 2011. Curated by its then-director <a href=\"/wiki/Jeffrey_Deitch\" title=\"Jeffrey Deitch\">Jeffrey Deitch</a> and associate curators <a href=\"/wiki/Aaron_Rose\" title=\"Aaron Rose\">Aaron Rose</a> and Roger Gastman, it surveyed the development of <a href=\"/wiki/Graffiti\" title=\"Graffiti\">graffiti</a> and global <a href=\"/wiki/Street_art\" title=\"Street art\">street art</a> from the 1970s to the present, covering the cities of <a href=\"/wiki/New_York_City\" title=\"New York City\">New York City</a>, the <a href=\"/wiki/West_Coast_of_the_United_States\" title=\"West Coast of the United States\">West Coast</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/London\" title=\"London\">London</a>, and <a href=\"/wiki/Sao_Paulo\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Sao Paulo\">Sao Paulo</a> with a focus on <a href=\"/wiki/Los_Angeles\" title=\"Los Angeles\">Los Angeles</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> It was supposed to travel to the <a href=\"/wiki/Brooklyn_Museum\" title=\"Brooklyn Museum\">Brooklyn Museum</a> from March 30 to July 8, 2012. The exhibit at the Brooklyn Museum was cancelled because of financial difficulties. <sup id=\"cite_ref-c_2-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-c-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>By some estimates, it was the most attended exhibition in the MOCA LA's history.<sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>Artists in the exhibition included: <a href=\"/wiki/Barry_McGee\" title=\"Barry McGee\">Barry McGee</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Lee_Qui%C3%B1ones\" title=\"Lee Qui\u00f1ones\">Lee Quinones</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/OSGEMEOS\" title=\"OSGEMEOS\">Os G\u00eameos</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Banksy\" title=\"Banksy\">Banksy</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Shepard_Fairey\" title=\"Shepard Fairey\">Shepard Fairey</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/TAKI_183\" title=\"TAKI 183\">TAKI 183</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Jean-Michel_Basquiat\" title=\"Jean-Michel Basquiat\">Jean-Michel Basquiat</a>, <a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Chaz_Boj%C3%B3rquez&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1\" class=\"new\" title=\"Chaz Boj\u00f3rquez (page does not exist)\">Chaz Boj\u00f3rquez</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/JR_(artist)\" title=\"JR (artist)\">JR</a>, <a href=\"/w/index.php?title=RISK_(artist)&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1\" class=\"new\" title=\"RISK (artist) (page does not exist)\">RISK</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Rammellzee\" title=\"Rammellzee\">Rammellzee</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Keith_Haring\" title=\"Keith Haring\">Keith Haring</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Kenny_Scharf\" title=\"Kenny Scharf\">Kenny Scharf</a>, <a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Angel_Ortiz_(artist)&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1\" class=\"new\" title=\"Angel Ortiz (artist) (page does not exist)\">Angel Ortiz</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Gusmano_Cesaretti\" title=\"Gusmano Cesaretti\">Gusmano Cesaretti</a> and others.<sup id=\"cite_ref-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-5\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-6\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>In early December 2010 Italian street artist <a href=\"/wiki/Blu_(artist)\" title=\"Blu (artist)\">Blu</a> was painted a mural on the side of the museum's Geffen Contemporary Wing to coincide with the exhibition.<sup id=\"cite_ref-7\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-7\">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup> Because the work's <a href=\"/wiki/Antiwar\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Antiwar\">antiwar</a> theme might be deemed offensive, the museum had it painted over within a day, and anonymous fellow artists avenged themselves by putting up posters of Deitch as an <a href=\"/wiki/Ayatollah\" title=\"Ayatollah\">ayatollah</a> holding a paint roller.<sup id=\"cite_ref-8\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-8\">&#91;8&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Art_in_the_Streets&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist columns references-column-width\" style=\"-moz-column-width: 30em; -webkit-column-width: 30em; column-width: 30em; list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation web\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.moca.org/museum/exhibitiondetail.php?id=443\">\"Past Exhibitions: Art in the Streets\"</a>. Moca.org.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.btitle=Past+Exhibitions%3A+Art+in+the+Streets&amp;rft.pub=Moca.org&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.moca.org%2Fmuseum%2Fexhibitiondetail.php%3Fid%3D443&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AArt+in+the+Streets\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-c-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-c_2-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation web\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://sites.moca.org/thecurve/2011/03/09/announcing-art-in-the-streets/\">\"Announcing Art in the Streets\"</a>. The Curve (MOCA LA). March 9, 2011.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.btitle=Announcing+Art+in+the+Streets&amp;rft.pub=The+Curve+%28MOCA+LA%29&amp;rft.date=2011-03-09&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fsites.moca.org%2Fthecurve%2F2011%2F03%2F09%2Fannouncing-art-in-the-streets%2F&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AArt+in+the+Streets\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-3\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation news\">Colacello, Bob (March 2013). \"How Do You Solve a Problem Like MOCA?\". <i>Vanity Fair</i>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.atitle=How+Do+You+Solve+a+Problem+Like+MOCA%3F&amp;rft.date=2013-03&amp;rft.aulast=Colacello&amp;rft.aufirst=Bob&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AArt+in+the+Streets\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-4\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-4\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation web\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.artnet.com/magazineus/reviews/drohojowska-philp/moca-art-in-the-streets-4-15-11.asp\">\"<span style=\"padding-left:0.2em;\">\"</span>Art in The Streets\" at MOCA LA\"</a>. <i>artnet Magazine</i><span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">2018-04-29</span></span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.jtitle=artnet+Magazine&amp;rft.atitle=%22Art+in+The+Streets%22+at+MOCA+LA&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.artnet.com%2Fmagazineus%2Freviews%2Fdrohojowska-philp%2Fmoca-art-in-the-streets-4-15-11.asp&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AArt+in+the+Streets\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-5\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-5\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation news\">Kennedy, Randy (2012-02-23). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://www.nytimes.com/2012/02/26/arts/design/rammellzees-work-and-reputation-re-emerge.html\">\"Rammellzee's Work and Reputation Re-emerge\"</a>. <i>The New York Times</i>. <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Serial_Number\" title=\"International Standard Serial Number\">ISSN</a>&#160;<a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"//www.worldcat.org/issn/0362-4331\">0362-4331</a><span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">2018-04-29</span></span>. <q>A bunkerlike, black-lighted re-creation of the Battle Station was one of the most talked-about pieces in \u201cArt in the Streets,\u201d a sprawling graffiti survey last year at the Museum of Contemporary Art, Los Angeles, organized by the museum\u2019s director, Jeffrey Deitch, who as a New York dealer had courted Rammellzee for years.</q></cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=The+New+York+Times&amp;rft.atitle=Rammellzee%E2%80%99s+Work+and+Reputation+Re-emerge&amp;rft.date=2012-02-23&amp;rft.issn=0362-4331&amp;rft.aulast=Kennedy&amp;rft.aufirst=Randy&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.nytimes.com%2F2012%2F02%2F26%2Farts%2Fdesign%2Frammellzees-work-and-reputation-re-emerge.html&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AArt+in+the+Streets\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-6\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-6\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation web\">Miranda, Carolina A. (2011-06-01). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.artnews.com/2011/06/01/art-in-the-streets/\">\"Art in the Streets\"</a>. <i>ARTnews</i><span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">2018-04-29</span></span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.jtitle=ARTnews&amp;rft.atitle=Art+in+the+Streets&amp;rft.date=2011-06-01&amp;rft.aulast=Miranda&amp;rft.aufirst=Carolina+A.&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.artnews.com%2F2011%2F06%2F01%2Fart-in-the-streets%2F&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AArt+in+the+Streets\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-7\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-7\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external free\" href=\"http://www.huffingtonpost.com/jaime-rojo-steven-harrington/censorship-moca-has-a-blu_b_796865.html#\">http://www.huffingtonpost.com/jaime-rojo-steven-harrington/censorship-moca-has-a-blu_b_796865.html#</a></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-8\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-8\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation news\">Somerstein, Rachel (April 26, 2011). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://archive.wired.com/magazine/2011/04/pl_art_revenge/\">\"<span style=\"padding-left:0.2em;\">\"</span>Burnt Umbrage: Studies in Anger<span style=\"padding-right:0.2em;\">\"</span>\"</a>. Wired.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.atitle=%22Burnt+Umbrage%3A+Studies+in+Anger%22&amp;rft.date=2011-04-26&amp;rft.aulast=Somerstein&amp;rft.aufirst=Rachel&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Farchive.wired.com%2Fmagazine%2F2011%2F04%2Fpl_art_revenge%2F&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AArt+in+the+Streets\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n</ol></div>\n\n<!-- \nNewPP limit report\nParsed by mw1326\nCached time: 20180908212810\nCache expiry: 1900800\nDynamic content: false\nCPU ti